post_text: THIS IS PROJECT PERIOD EXHIBITION! Get a passport and travel around the world through food; support the ocean by buying a jellyfish made from trash collected on the beach (including a balloon the kids traced to a CT school who will be receiving a letter); eat homemade basil sage butter; visit a pop-up bike repair shop; filter water and see a slideshow of 60 miles of canoeing; meditate for two minutes; and experience a graveyard, Africa, Seattle, and outer space through 8 hand painted rooms. So proud of these students! #aroundtheworld #canoe-about #mindfulmoves #let’ssea #DIY #recycle #sweetsuite #livelocal #independentstudy #mvpubliccharterschool #projectbasedlearning #thisisprojectperiod @ Martha'S Vineyard Charter School

post_text: THIS IS PROJECT PERIOD “Canoe-About” Eight 7th-11th graders, one week, 60 miles, and five canoes. In West Branch Penobscot River (from Roll Dam to Forestry Point) in the deep wilderness of spectacular Maine, these kids learned to paddle - but they also learned about unplugging (no cell service whatsoever), wilderness ethics, and cooperative routines. Thank you @jonahamaidoff @caseyahayward for your steadfast commitment to beauty, adventure, simplicity, and authentic education. 🙏🏻🌲🛶#projectbasedlearning #offthegrid #camping #canoeing #unplugging #maine #thisisprojectperiod #mvpubliccharterschool #paddle #penobscot

post_text:
THIS IS PROJECT PERIOD
📸🎨“Art Exploration and Photography” run by Emily LaPierre (who is leaving us to be the VH Children’s Librarian 👏🏻😪) students traveled around MV looking at our island from a purely artistic perspective and taking photos. Here they are at the Morgan learning center using paints and watercolors on canvas in both seated and standing positions; at Owen Park creating found art and looking at small & large perspective; and at the field gallery sculpture-gazing, making art, and discussing which pieces in the gallery spoke to them - pretty amazing when some picked Charter Alum @walkertroman ‘s paintings! 🙌🏻#projectbasedlearning #art #perspective #islandarts #photography #arteducation 📸 @scottyg15 @emah09 & students!

post_text:
“The Charter School allowed me to grow in ways I never could’ve elsewhere,” said Keith Chatinover. Thank goodness for that. MVPCS has been lucky to have Keith Chatinover as a student since 6th grade, and Middlebury College and State Rep Dylan Fernandes are lucky to lead him into his bright future. No one deserved the Massachusetts High School Activist of the Year Award more, nor the MV League of Women Voters scholarship, nor the Thomas H. Lee and Barbara F. Lee Award from the MV Permanent Endowment. Indeed, Keith’s tireless work for environmental and social justice and all he does to further the fight against gun violence, not to mention the focus and enthusiasm he brought to his learning every school day has been something to behold. The walls and the people of the Charter School will miss this human - and his relentless idealism - immensely.
Excellent photo by classmate @dashiell.rozum #seniorprofiles #mvpubliccharterschool #proud #graduation @rep.dylanfernandes @middleburycollege @leagueofwomenvoters

post_text:
Troy Vanderhoop (left) is excited for the next chapter. He’s always wanted to work in law enforcement and plans to attend Cape Cod Community College in the fall to follow that dream. In the meantime he’s working hard to run his own music booking company and start a clothing line. About the Charter School, which he joined in 11th grade, he said “it was fun,” which means a lot coming from this guy 👉🏻

post_text: Claudia Motta chose Emmanuel College over the many other universities that accepted her because it’s small, diverse, and in the center of Boston. She’ll continue following her passion for healing people - since starting at MVPCS in 10th grade she’s had mentorships with island doctors, conducted loads of research, and focused all her school portfolios on the medical field. She also loves to travel and has already been to Cuba, Brazil, and Italy. Of the Charter School, she says, “I love the community feel, and how everyone is so nice and respectful.” Thanks, Claudia! We’re proud of your hard work and excited for your bright future! ☀️ #seniorprofiles #futuredoctor #onward #proud #graduation #mvpubliccharterschool @emmanuelcollege you’re one lucky school!

“Scott Goldin is pursuing a master’s in education through Lesley University’s Middle School Education Math/Science program. Scott teaches math and science at the Martha’s Vineyard Public Charter School, where he developed and implemented an initiative to remove food waste from the school’s waste stream. He is the Charter School garden coordinator for Island Grown Schools, and is involved with a new Island project called M.V. Zero Waste.” #congrats #visionfellowship #mvpubliccharterschool #proud

post_text: Meet MVPCS Senior Eleanor Dankert. She’s passionate about writing and is currently working on various book chapters at school for her senior portfolio. Eleanor is excited to be attending Massachusetts College of Liberal Arts (MCLA) in the fall. She came to the Charter School in the middle of 8th grade and says, perhaps without realizing its poignancy, “After going to many schools, I just feel like I can be myself here.” Congratulations on your upcoming graduation Eleanor! We’re proud of all you’ve accomplished. #charterseniors #onward #proud #graduation #mvpubliccharterschool

post_text:
Here’s to celebrating International Women’s Day yesterday, today, and EVERY DAY. We’re so proud of our girls and so grateful for our teachers and community. Some humbling and motivating statistics:
1. Globally, 65 million girls are not in school.
2. There are 31 million girls of primary school age not in school. Seventeen million of these girls will probably never attend school in their lifetimes.
3. Of the 123 million young people between the ages of 15 and 24 who cannot read or write, 61 percent of them are women.
4. There are 33 million fewer girls than boys in primary school.
5. Girls with eight years of education are four times less likely to marry as children.
6. A girl with an extra year of education can earn 20 percent more as an adult.
7. A child born to a mother who can read and write is 50 percent more likely to survive past the age of 5.
8. Educated mothers are more than twice as likely to send their children to school.

Here’s to celebrating International Women’s Day yesterday, today, and EVERY DAY. We’re so proud of our girls and so grateful for our teachers and community. Some humbling and motivating statistics:
1. Globally, 65 million girls are not in school.
2. There are 31 million girls of primary school age not in school. Seventeen million of these girls will probably never attend school in their lifetimes.
3. Of the 123 million young people between the ages of 15 and 24 who cannot read or write, 61 percent of them are women.
4. There are 33 million fewer girls than boys in primary school.
5. Girls with eight years of education are four times less likely to marry as children.
6. A girl with an extra year of education can earn 20 percent more as an adult.
7. A child born to a mother who can read and write is 50 percent more likely to survive past the age of 5.
8. Educated mothers are more than twice as likely to send their children to school.

post_text: Little League early registration and tryout dates will be announced soon! Don’t miss out on $25 off! Spread the word & stay tuned! ⚾️👂🏻⚾️👀⚾️
shared_text:
MV Little League
January 20, 2018 at 1:16 PM ·

I woke up this morning wondering if baseball is going to start soon? The sun is setting later, the weather is warmer compare to the 1 degree that kept us inside, and it is about two months away before we start Tryouts! I also realize that we have to start registering our kids to have tryouts.🤔 Parents and family the countdown for early registration is coming real soon!! Please start spreading the word of the $25. off special for early registration. I will be announcing when we are opening our 2018 Martha's Vineyard Little League website, for signup real soon. Please stay tune in with Facebook. 😃

post_text: Twice a year all our 5th-12th graders get together to delve into a subject they’re drawn to and in some cases completely passionate about (case in point here). Then they spend ten full school days making it happen. Here’s a snippet of the Project Period devoted to learning about and making music. These kids wrote 13 songs! Thank you @willymason @isaactaylormusic and many others for your guidance and talent! #ThisIsProjectPeriod
